# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: anatomically-modern-humans
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Extinct species of the genus *Homo* include *Homo erectus* (extant from roughly 2,000,000 to 100,000 years ago) and a number of other species (by some authors considered subspecies of either *H. sapiens* or *H. erectus*).
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] The divergence of the lineage leading to *H. sapiens* out of ancestral *H. erectus* (or an intermediate species such as *Homo antecessor*) is estimated to have occurred in Africa roughly 500,000 years ago.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] The earliest fossil evidence of early modern humans appears in Africa around 300,000 years ago, with the earliest genetic splits among modern people, according to some evidence, dating to around the same time.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Sustained archaic human admixture with modern humans is known to have taken place both in Africa and (following the recent Out-Of-Africa expansion) in Eurasia, between about 100,000 and 30,000 years ago.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] The binomial name *Homo sapiens* was coined by Linnaeus, 1758.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] The Latin noun *homō* (genitive *hominis*) means "human being", while the participle *sapiēns* means "discerning, wise, sensible", or taken together essentially "intelligent human".
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] The species was initially thought to have emerged from a predecessor within the genus *Homo* around 300,000 to 200,000 years ago.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] A problem with the morphological classification of "anatomically modern" was that it would not have included certain extant populations.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] For this reason, a lineage-based (cladistic) definition of *H. sapiens* has been suggested, in which *H. sapiens* would by definition refer to the modern human lineage following the split from the Neanderthal lineage.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Such a cladistic definition would extend the age of *H. sapiens* to over 500,000 years.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Estimates for the split between the Homo sapiens line and combined Neanderthal/Denisovan line range from between 503,000 and 565,000 years ago; between 550,000 and 765,000 years ago; and (based on rates of dental evolution) possibly more than 800,000 years ago.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Extant human populations have historically been divided into subspecies, but since around the 1980s, the consensus has been to subsume all extant groups into a single species, *H. sapiens*, avoiding division into subspecies altogether.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Some sources show Neanderthals (*H. neanderthalensis*) as a subspecies (*H. sapiens neanderthalensis*).
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Similarly, the discovered specimens of the *H. rhodesiensis* species have been classified by some as a subspecies (*H. sapiens rhodesiensis*), although it remains more common to treat these last two as separate species within the genus *Homo* rather than as subspecies within *H. sapiens*.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] All humans are considered to be a part of the subspecies *H. sapiens sapiens*, a designation which has been a matter of debate since a species is usually not given a subspecies category unless there is evidence of multiple distinct subspecies.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] The divergence of the lineage that would lead to *H. sapiens* out of archaic human varieties derived from *H. erectus*, is estimated as having taken place over 500,000 years ago (marking the split of the *H. sapiens* lineage from ancestors shared with other known archaic hominins).
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] 259,000 years ago), and the Omo remains from Ethiopia (ca.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] 195,000, or, as more recently dated, ca.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] An mtDNA study in 2019 proposed an origin of modern humans in Botswana (and a Khoisan split) of around 200,000 years.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] However, this proposal has been widely criticized by scholars, with the recent evidence overall (genetic, fossil, and archaeological) supporting an origin for *H. sapiens* approximately 100,000 years earlier and in a broader region of Africa than the study proposes.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] In September 2019, scientists proposed that the earliest *H. sapiens* (and last common human ancestor to modern humans) arose between 350,000 and 260,000 years ago through a merging of populations in East and South Africa.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] An alternative suggestion defines *H. sapiens* cladistically as including the lineage of modern humans since the split from the lineage of Neanderthals, roughly 500,000 to 800,000 years ago.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Since the 1970s, the Omo remains, originally dated to some 195,000 years ago, have often been taken as the conventional cut-off point for the emergence of "anatomically modern humans".
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Since the 2000s, the discovery of older remains with comparable characteristics, and the discovery of ongoing hybridization between "modern" and "archaic" populations after the time of the Omo remains, have opened up a renewed debate on the age of *H. sapiens* in journalistic publications.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] *H. s. idaltu*, dated to 160,000 years ago, has been postulated as an extinct subspecies of *H. sapiens* in 2003.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] *H. neanderthalensis*, which became extinct about 40,000 years ago, was also at one point considered to be a subspecies, *H. s. neanderthalensis*.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] The term Middle Paleolithic is intended to cover the time between the first emergence of *H. sapiens* (roughly 300,000 years ago) and the period held by some to mark the emergence of full behavioral modernity (roughly by 50,000 years ago, corresponding to the start of the Upper Paleolithic).
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Many of the early modern human finds, like those of Jebel Irhoud, Omo, Herto, Florisbad, Skhul, and Peștera cu Oase, exhibit a mix of archaic and modern traits.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Skhul V, for example, has prominent brow ridges and a projecting face.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] However, the brain case is quite rounded and distinct from that of the Neanderthals and is similar to the brain case of modern humans.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] It is uncertain whether the robust traits of some of the early modern humans like Skhul V reflects mixed ancestry or retention of older traits.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] The "gracile" or lightly built skeleton of anatomically modern humans has been connected to a change in behavior, including increased cooperation and "resource transport".
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] There is evidence that the characteristic human brain development, especially the prefrontal cortex, was due to "an exceptional acceleration of metabolome evolution ... paralleled by a drastic reduction in muscle strength.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] *H. heidelbergensis* already had intellectual and cognitive skills like anticipatory planning, thinking and acting that so far have only been attributed to modern humans.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] The ongoing admixture events within anatomically modern human populations make it difficult to estimate the age of the matrilinear and patrilinear most recent common ancestors of modern populations (Mitochondrial Eve and Y-chromosomal Adam).
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Estimates of the age of Y-chromosomal Adam have been pushed back significantly with the discovery of an ancient Y-chromosomal lineage in 2013, to likely beyond 300,000 years ago.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] There have, however, been no reports of the survival of Y-chromosomal or mitochondrial DNA clearly deriving from archaic humans (which would push back the age of the most recent patrilinear or matrilinear ancestor beyond 500,000 years).
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Fossil teeth found at Qesem Cave (Israel) and dated to between 400,000 and 200,000 years ago have been compared to the dental material from the younger (120,000–80,000 years ago) Skhul and Qafzeh hominins.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Dispersal of early *H. sapiens* began soon after its emergence, as evidenced by the North African Jebel Irhoud finds (dated to around 315,000 years ago).
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] There is indirect evidence for *H. sapiens* presence in West Asia around 270,000 years ago.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] The Florisbad Skull from Florisbad, South Africa, dated to about 259,000 years ago, has also been classified as representing early *H. sapiens*.Scerri (2018), pp.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Among extant populations, the Khoi-San (or "Capoid") hunters-gatherers of Southern Africa may represent the human population with the earliest possible divergence within the group *Homo sapiens sapiens*.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Their separation time has been estimated in a 2017 study to be between 350 and 260,000 years ago, compatible with the estimated age of early *H. sapiens*.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] In July 2019, anthropologists reported the discovery of 210,000 year old remains of a *H. sapiens* and 170,000 year old remains of a *H. neanderthalensis* in Apidima Cave, Peloponnese, Greece, more than 150,000 years older than previous *H. sapiens* finds in Europe.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] A significant dispersal event, within Africa and to West Asia, is associated with the African megadroughts during MIS 5, beginning 130,000 years ago.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] A 2011 study located the origin of basal population of contemporary human populations at 130,000 years ago, with the Khoi-San representing an "ancestral population cluster" located in southwestern Africa (near the coastal border of Namibia and Angola).
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] While early modern human expansion in Sub-Saharan Africa before 130 kya persisted, early expansion to North Africa and Asia appears to have mostly disappeared by the end of MIS5 (75,000 years ago), and is known only from fossil evidence and from archaic admixture.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Eurasia was re-populated by early modern humans in the so-called "recent out-of-Africa migration" post-dating MIS5, beginning around 70,000–50,000 years ago.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Some evidence suggests that an early wave of humans may have reached the Americas by about 40,000–25,000 years ago.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] The assumption of complete replacement has been revised in the 2010s with the discovery of admixture events (introgression) of populations of *H. sapiens* with populations of archaic humans over the period of between roughly 100,000 and 30,000 years ago, both in Eurasia and in Sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Neanderthal admixture, in the range of 1–4%, is found in all modern populations outside of Africa, including in Europeans, Asians, Papua New Guineans, Australian Aboriginals, Native Americans, and other non-Africans.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] This suggests that interbreeding between Neanderthals and anatomically modern humans took place after the recent "out of Africa" migration, likely between 60,000 and 40,000 years ago.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Recent admixture analyses have added to the complexity, finding that Eastern Neanderthals derive up to 2% of their ancestry from anatomically modern humans who left Africa some 100 kya.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] The extent of Neanderthal admixture (and introgression of genes acquired by admixture) varies significantly between contemporary racial groups, being absent in Africans, intermediate in Europeans and highest in East Asians.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Certain genes related to UV-light adaptation introgressed from Neanderthals have been found to have been selected for in East Asians specifically from 45,000 years ago until around 5,000 years ago.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] The extent of archaic admixture is of the order of about 1% to 4% in Europeans and East Asians, and highest among Melanesians (the last also having Denisova hominin admixture at 4% to 6% in addition to neanderthal admixture).
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Cumulatively, about 20% of the Neanderthal genome is estimated to remain present spread in contemporary populations.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] According to a study published in 2020, there are indications that 2% to 19% (or about ≃6.6 and ≃7.0%) of the DNA of four West African populations may have come from an unknown archaic hominin which split from the ancestor of humans and Neanderthals between 360 kya to 1.02 mya.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Generally, modern humans are more lightly built (or more "gracile") than the more "robust" archaic humans.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Nevertheless, contemporary humans exhibit high variability in many physiological traits, and may exhibit remarkable "robustness".
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] There are still a number of physiological details which can be taken as reliably differentiating the physiology of Neanderthals vs. anatomically modern humans.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] In a convention popular in the 1990s, Neanderthals were classified as a subspecies of *H. sapiens*, as *H. s. neanderthalensis*, while anatomically modern humans (or European early modern humans), was taken to refer to "Cro-Magnon" or *H. s. sapiens*.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Under this nomenclature (Neanderthals considered *H. sapiens*), the term "anatomically modern *Homo sapiens*" has also been used to refer to European early modern humans ("Cro-Magnons").
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] It has since become more common to designate Neanderthals as a separate species, *H. neanderthalensis*, so that anatomically modern human in the European context refers to *H. sapiens*, but the question is by no means resolved.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] In this more narrow definition of *H. sapiens*, the subspecies *Homo sapiens idaltu*, discovered in 2003, also falls under the umbrella of "anatomically modern".
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] The recognition of *H. sapiens idaltu* as a valid subspecies of the anatomically modern human lineage would justify the description of contemporary humans with the subspecies name *Homo sapiens sapiens*.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] However, biological anthropologist Chris Stringer does not consider *idaltu* distinct enough within *H. sapiens* to warrant its own subspecies designation.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] A further division of anatomically modern human into "early" or "robust" vs.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] "post-glacial" or "gracile" subtypes has since been used for convenience.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] The emergence of "gracile anatomically modern human" is taken to reflect a process towards a smaller and more fine-boned skeleton beginning around 50,000–30,000 years ago.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] The cranium lacks a pronounced occipital bun in the neck, a bulge that anchored considerable neck muscles in Neanderthals.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Modern humans, even the earlier ones, generally have a larger fore-brain than the archaic people, so that the brain sits above rather than behind the eyes.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] This will usually (though not always) give a higher forehead, and reduced brow ridge.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Early modern people and some living people do however have quite pronounced brow ridges, but they differ from those of archaic forms by having both a supraorbital foramen or notch, forming a groove through the ridge above each eye.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] This splits the ridge into a central part and two distal parts.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] In current humans, often only the central section of the ridge is preserved (if it is preserved at all).
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] This contrasts with archaic humans, where the brow ridge is pronounced and unbroken.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Modern humans commonly have a steep, even vertical forehead whereas their predecessors had foreheads that sloped strongly backwards.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] According to Desmond Morris, the vertical forehead in humans plays an important role in human communication through eyebrow movements and forehead skin wrinkling.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Brain size in both Neanderthals and anatomically modern humans is significantly larger on average (but overlapping in range) than brain size in *H. erectus*.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Neanderthal and anatomically modern human brain sizes are in the same range, but there are differences in the relative sizes of individual brain areas, with significantly larger visual systems in Neanderthals than in anatomically modern humans.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Compared to archaic people, anatomically modern humans have smaller, differently shaped teeth.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] This results in a smaller, more receded dentary, making the rest of the jaw-line stand out, giving an often quite prominent chin.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] The central part of the mandible forming the chin carries a triangularly shaped area forming the apex of the chin called the **mental Trigon**, not found in archaic humans.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Particularly in living populations, the use of fire and tools requires fewer jaw muscles, giving slender, more gracile jaws.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Compared to archaic people, modern humans have smaller, lower faces.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] The body skeletons of even the earliest and most robustly built modern humans were less robust than those of Neanderthals (and - from what little we know - from Denisovans), having essentially modern proportions.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Particularly regarding the long bones of the limbs, the distal bones (the radius/ulna and tibia/fibula) are nearly the same size or slightly shorter than the proximal bones (the humerus and femur).
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] In ancient people, particularly Neanderthals, the distal bones were shorter, usually thought to be an adaptation to cold climate.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] The same adaptation is found in some modern people living in the polar regions.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Height ranges overlap between Neanderthals and anatomically modern humans, with Neanderthal averages cited as 164 to 168 cm (65 to 66 in) and 152 to 156 cm (60 to 61 in) for males and females, respectively, which is largely identical to pre-industrial average heights for anatomically modern humans.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Contemporary national averages range between 158 to 184 cm (62 to 72 in) in males and 147 to 172 cm (58 to 68 in) in females.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Neanderthal ranges approximate the contemporary height distribution measured among Malay people, for one.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Following the peopling of Africa some 130,000 years ago, and the recent Out-of-Africa expansion some 70,000 to 50,000 years ago, some sub-populations of *H. sapiens* had been essentially isolated for tens of thousands of years prior to the early modern Age of Discovery.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Combined with archaic admixture this has resulted in significant genetic variation, which in some instances has been shown to be the result of directional selection taking place over the past 15,000 years, i.e., significantly later than possible archaic admixture events.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Some climatic adaptations, such as high-altitude adaptation in humans, are thought to have been acquired by archaic admixture.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Introgression of genetic variants acquired by Neanderthal admixture have different distributions in European and East Asians, reflecting differences in recent selective pressures.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] A 2014 study reported that Neanderthal-derived variants found in East Asian populations showed clustering in functional groups related to immune and haematopoietic pathways, while European populations showed clustering in functional groups related to the lipid catabolic process.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] A 2017 study found correlation of Neanderthal admixture in phenotypic traits in modern European populations.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Physiological or phenotypical changes have been traced to Upper Paleolithic mutations, such as the East Asian variant of the *EDAR* gene, dated to c.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Recent divergence of Eurasian lineages was sped up significantly during the Last Glacial Maximum, the Mesolithic and the Neolithic, due to increased selection pressures and due to founder effects associated with migration.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Alleles predictive of light skin have been found in Neanderthals, but the alleles for light skin in Europeans and East Asians, associated with KITLG and ASIP, are (as of 2012) thought to have not been acquired by archaic admixture but recent mutations since the Last Glacial Maximum.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Phenotypes associated with the "white" or "Caucasian" populations of Western Eurasian stock emerge during the Last Glacial Maximum, from about 19,000 years ago.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Average cranial capacity in modern human populations varies in the range of 1,200 to 1,450 cm3 for adult males.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Larger cranial volume is associated with climatic region, the largest averages being found in populations of Siberia and the Arctic.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Both Neanderthal and European early modern humans had somewhat larger cranial volumes on average than modern Europeans, suggesting the relaxation of selection pressures for larger brain volume after the end of the Last Glacial Maximum.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Examples for still later adaptations related to agriculture and animal domestication including East Asian types of ADH1B associated with rice domestication, or lactase persistence, are due to recent selection pressures.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] An even more recent adaptation has been proposed for the Austronesian Sama-Bajau, developed under selection pressures associated with subsisting on freediving over the past thousand years or so.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Behavioral modernity, involving the development of language, figurative art and early forms of religion (etc.) is taken to have arisen before 40,000 years ago, marking the beginning of the Upper Paleolithic (in African contexts also known as the Later Stone Age).
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] There is considerable debate regarding whether the earliest anatomically modern humans behaved similarly to recent or existing humans.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] The term Upper Paleolithic is intended to cover the period since the rapid expansion of modern humans throughout Eurasia, which coincides with the first appearance of Paleolithic art such as cave paintings and the development of technological innovation such as the spear-thrower.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] The Upper Paleolithic begins around 50,000 to 40,000 years ago, and also coincides with the disappearance of archaic humans such as the Neanderthals.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] The term "behavioral modernity" is somewhat disputed.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] It is most often used for the set of characteristics marking the Upper Paleolithic, but some scholars use "behavioral modernity" for the emergence of *H. sapiens* around 200,000 years ago, while others use the term for the rapid developments occurring around 50,000 years ago.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] It has been proposed that the emergence of behavioral modernity was a gradual process.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] The equivalent of the Eurasian Upper Paleolithic in African archaeology is known as the Later Stone Age, also beginning roughly 40,000 years ago.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] There is also a suggestion that "pressure flaking best explains the morphology of lithic artifacts recovered from the c.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] 75-ka Middle Stone Age levels at Blombos Cave, South Africa.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] These have been dated to approximately 71,000 years ago.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] The researchers suggest that their research "shows that microlithic technology originated early in South Africa by 71 kya, evolved over a vast time span (c.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] 11,000 years), and was typically coupled to complex heat treatment that persisted for nearly 100,000 years.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] This might have led to human groups who were seeking refuge from the inland droughts, expanded along the coastal marshes rich in shellfish and other resources.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Since sea levels were low due to so much water tied up in glaciers, such marshlands would have occurred all along the southern coasts of Eurasia.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] The use of rafts and boats may well have facilitated exploration of offshore islands and travel along the coast, and eventually permitted expansion to New Guinea and then to Australia.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] In addition, a variety of other evidence of abstract imagery, widened subsistence strategies, and other "modern" behaviors has been discovered in Africa, especially South, North, and East Africa, predating 50,000 years ago (with some predating 100,000 years ago).
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] The Blombos Cave site in South Africa, for example, is famous for rectangular slabs of ochre engraved with geometric designs.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Using multiple dating techniques, the site was confirmed to be around 77,000 and 100,000–75,000 years old.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Ostrich egg shell containers engraved with geometric designs dating to 60,000 years ago were found at Diepkloof, South Africa.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] In 2008, an ochre processing workshop likely for the production of paints was uncovered dating to ca.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] 100,000 years ago at Blombos Cave, South Africa.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Analysis shows that a liquefied pigment-rich mixture was produced and stored in the two abalone shells, and that ochre, bone, charcoal, grindstones and hammer-stones also formed a composite part of the toolkits.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Modern behaviors, such as the making of shell beads, bone tools and arrows, and the use of ochre pigment, are evident at a Kenyan site by 78,000-67,000 years ago.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Evidence of early stone-tipped projectile weapons (a characteristic tool of *Homo sapiens*), the stone tips of javelins or throwing spears, were discovered in 2013 at the Ethiopian site of Gademotta, and date to around 279,000 years ago.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Expanding subsistence strategies beyond big-game hunting and the consequential diversity in tool types have been noted as signs of behavioral modernity.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] A number of South African sites have shown an early reliance on aquatic resources from fish to shellfish.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Pinnacle Point, in particular, shows exploitation of marine resources as early as 120,000 years ago, perhaps in response to more arid conditions inland.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Establishing a reliance on predictable shellfish deposits, for example, could reduce mobility and facilitate complex social systems and symbolic behavior.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Blombos Cave and Site 440 in Sudan both show evidence of fishing as well.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Taphonomic change in fish skeletons from Blombos Cave have been interpreted as capture of live fish, clearly an intentional human behavior.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Humans in North Africa (Nazlet Sabaha, Egypt) are known to have dabbled in chert mining, as early as ≈100,000 years ago, for the construction of stone tools.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] Evidence was found in 2018, dating to about 320,000 years ago at the site of Olorgesailie in Kenya, of the early emergence of modern behaviors including: the trade and long-distance transportation of resources (such as obsidian), the use of pigments, and the possible making of projectile points.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/anatomically-modern-humans] In 2019, further evidence of Middle Stone Age complex projectile weapons in Africa was found at Aduma, Ethiopia, dated 100,000–80,000 years ago, in the form of points considered likely to belong to darts delivered by spear throwers.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] In biological taxonomy, a **synonym** is one of two or more scientific names that apply to the same taxon.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] The botanical and zoological codes of nomenclature treat the concept of synonymy differently.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] In botanical nomenclature, a synonym is a scientific name that applies to a taxon that now goes by a different scientific name.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] For example, Linnaeus was the first to give a scientific name (under the currently used system of scientific nomenclature) to the Norway spruce, which he called *Pinus abies*.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] This name is no longer in use, so it is now a synonym of the current scientific name, *Picea abies*.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] In zoology, moving a species from one genus to another results in a different binomen, but the name is considered an alternative combination rather than a synonym.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] However, *Araschnia levana* is not a synonym of *Papilio levana* in the taxonomic sense employed by the International Code of Zoological Nomenclature.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] Unlike synonyms in other contexts, in taxonomy a synonym is not interchangeable with the name of which it is a synonym.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] In taxonomy, synonyms are not equals, but have a different status.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] For any taxon with a particular circumscription, position, and rank, only one scientific name is considered to be the correct one at any given time (this correct name is to be determined by applying the relevant code of nomenclature).
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] A synonym cannot exist in isolation: it is always an alternative to a different scientific name.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] Given that the correct name of a taxon depends on the taxonomic viewpoint used (resulting in a particular circumscription, position and rank) a name that is one taxonomist's synonym may be another taxonomist's correct name (and *vice versa*).
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] Synonyms may arise whenever the same taxon is described and named independently more than once.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] They may also arise when existing taxa are changed, as when two taxa are joined to become one, a species is moved to a different genus, a variety is moved to a different species, etc.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] Synonyms also come about when the codes of nomenclature change, so that older names are no longer acceptable; for example, *Erica herbacea* L. has been rejected in favour of the conserved name of *Erica carnea* L. and is thus its synonym.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] Thus *Oxford Dictionaries Online* defines the term as "a taxonomic name which has the same application as another, especially one which has been superseded and is no longer valid".
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] In handbooks and general texts, it is useful to have synonyms mentioned as such after the current scientific name, so as to avoid confusion.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] For example, if the much-advertised name change should go through and the scientific name of the fruit fly were changed to *Sophophora melanogaster*, it would be very helpful if any mention of this name was accompanied by "(syn.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] Synonyms used in this way may not always meet the strict definitions of the term "synonym" in the formal rules of nomenclature which govern scientific names *(see below)*.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] Changes of scientific name have two causes: they may be taxonomic or nomenclatural.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] A name change may be caused by changes in the circumscription, position or rank of a taxon, representing a change in taxonomic, scientific insight (as would be the case for the fruit fly, mentioned above).
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] A name change may be due to purely nomenclatural reasons, that is, based on the rules of nomenclature; as for example when an older name is (re)discovered which has priority over the current name.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] In general, name changes for nomenclatural reasons have become less frequent over time as the rules of nomenclature allow for the current name to be conserved (i.e. kept, even though contrary to other rules), so as to promote stability of scientific names.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] In zoological nomenclature, codified in the *International Code of Zoological Nomenclature*, synonyms are different scientific names of the same taxonomic rank that pertain to the same taxon.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] For example, a particular species could, over time, have had two or more species-rank names published for it, while the same is applicable at higher ranks such as genera, families, orders, etc.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] In each case, the earliest published name is called the **senior synonym**, while the later name is the **junior synonym**.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] One basic principle of zoological nomenclature is that the earliest correctly published (and thus available) name, the senior synonym, by default takes precedence in naming rights, and therefore, unless other restrictions interfere, must be used for the taxon.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] However, junior synonyms are still important to document, because if the earliest name cannot be used (for example, because the same spelling had previously been used for a name established for another taxon), then the next available junior synonym must be used for the taxon.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] For example, John Edward Gray published the name *Antilocapra anteflexa* in 1855 for a species of pronghorn, based on a pair of horns.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] However, it is now commonly accepted that his specimen was an unusual individual of the species *Antilocapra americana* published by George Ord in 1815.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] Ord's name thus takes precedence, with *Antilocapra anteflexa* being a junior subjective synonym.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] Objective synonyms are common at the rank of genera, because for various reasons two genera may contain the same type species; these are objective synonyms.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] In many cases researchers established new generic names because they thought this was necessary or did not know that others had previously established another genus for the same group of species.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] On the same occasion, *Helix* is also a synonym of *Pomatia*, but it is older and so it has precedence.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] At the species level, subjective synonyms are common because of an unexpectedly large range of variation in a species, or simple ignorance about an earlier description, may lead a biologist to describe a newly discovered specimen as a new species.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] A common reason for objective synonyms at this level is the creation of a replacement name.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] A junior synonym can be given precedence over a senior synonym, primarily when the senior name has not been used since 1899, and the junior name is in common use.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] The older name may be declared to be a *nomen oblitum*, and the junior name declared a *nomen protectum*.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] This rule exists primarily to prevent the confusion that would result if a well-known name, with a large accompanying body of literature, were to be replaced by a completely unfamiliar name.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] An example is the European land snail *Petasina edentula* (Draparnaud, 1805).
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] In 2002, researchers found that an older name *Helix depilata* Draparnaud, 1801 referred to the same species, but this name had never been used after 1899 and was fixed as a *nomen oblitum* under this rule by Falkner *et al.* 2002.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] Such a reversal of precedence is also possible if the senior synonym was established after 1900, but only if the International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature (ICZN) approves an application.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] (Here the C in ICZN stands for Commission, not Code as it does at the beginning of § Zoology.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] To qualify as a synonym in zoology, a name must be properly published in accordance with the rules.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] Manuscript names and names that were mentioned without any description (*nomina nuda*) are not considered as synonyms in zoological nomenclature.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] In botanical nomenclature, a synonym is a name that is not correct for the circumscription, position, and rank of the taxon as considered in the particular botanical publication.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] It is always "a synonym of the correct scientific name", but which name is correct depends on the taxonomic opinion of the author.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] Scientific papers may include lists of taxa, synonymizing existing taxa and (in some cases) listing references to them.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] The status of a synonym may be indicated by symbols, as for instance in a system proposed for use in paleontology by Rudolf Richter.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] In that system a `v` before the year would indicate that the authors have inspected the original material; a `.` that they take on the responsibility for the act of synonymizing the taxa.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] The accurate use of scientific names, including synonyms, is crucial in biomedical and pharmacological research involving plants.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] Failure to use correct botanical nomenclature can lead to ambiguity, hinder reproducibility of results, and potentially cause errors in medicine.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] Best practices for publication suggest that researchers should provide the currently accepted binomial with author citation, relevant synonyms, and the accepted family name according to the Angiosperm Phylogeny Group III classification.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] This practice ensures clear communication, allows proper linking of research to existing literature, and provides insight into phylogenetic relationships that may be relevant to shared chemical constituents or physiological effects.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] Online databases now make it easy for researchers to access correct nomenclature and synonymy information for plant species.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] The traditional concept of synonymy is often expanded in taxonomic literature to include *pro parte* (or "for part") synonyms.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym-taxonomy] These are caused by splits and circumscriptional changes.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym] A **synonym** is a word, morpheme, or phrase that has a similar or identical meaning to another word, morpheme, or phrase in a given language.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym] For example, in English, words like *begin*, *start*, *commence*, and *initiate* are synonyms: they are *synonymous.* The standard test for synonymy is substitution: one form can be used interchangeably without changing the meaning of the sentence.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym] Words may be synonymous in only one particular sense: for example, *long* and *extended* in the context of *long time* or *extended time* are synonymous, but *long* cannot be used in the phrase *extended family*.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym] Synonyms with identical meanings share a seme or denotational sememe, whereas those with inexactly similar meanings share a broader denotational or connotational sememe and overlap within a semantic field.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym] The former are sometimes known as cognitive synonyms, and the latter are referred to as near-synonyms, plesionyms, or poecilonyms.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym] Some lexicographers argue that no synonyms are identical (in all contexts or social levels of language) due to differences in etymology, orthography, phonic qualities, connotations, ambiguous meanings, and usage.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym] For example, *feline* is more formal than *cat*, and a *long arm* is not the same as an *extended arm*, as *long* and *extended* are not always interchangeable.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym] Synonyms can also be used as euphemisms.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym] Metonymy is sometimes a type of synonymy.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym] For example, *White House* is often used as a synonym of *the administration* to refer to the U.S. executive branch under a specific president.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym] In this context, *metonymy* functions as a hyponym of *synonymy*.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym] The study of synonymy, polysemy, hyponymy, and hypernymy is essential in information science for taxonomy and ontology.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym] This analysis is also important in pedagogy and machine learning for word-sense disambiguation.
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym] The term synonym is derived from the Latin word **synōnymum**, which was borrowed from the Ancient Greek word **synōnymon** (συνώνυμον).
[src:anatomically-modern-humans/synonym] It is composed of the Greek elements **sýn** (σύν, meaning 'together, similar, alike') and *-*ōnym*-* (-ωνυμ-), a form of **onoma** (ὄνομα, meaning 'name').
